            "answer_text": "Of course, they do.  WW2 For starters, the Germans placed emphasis on the engineering aspect of their weapons, building grand superweapons that would be deemed a feat of engineering even till this day. This was done as a means of propaganda, to portray Germany as a strong and advanced military power.  A Nazi Propaganda poster showcasing german technological military might One example of this mindset has to be the schwerer gustav, which was chambered in 800mm.  Schwewer Gustav  800mm While the Schwewer Gustav was operational, It was more of a political statement by Hitler rather than an actual tool of war.  Hitler That was roughly the German mindset during the war and It was only later in the war that they realized that wars are not won by expensive super weapons, but rather the tactics and the weaponry the standard military had access to, which were things that were both neglected by the Germans earlier in the war, as they let themselves get giddy with victory. Another nation\u2019s whose psychology could be seen in Its weapons is Japan.  Japan Japan psychological mindset was rather backwards for Its time, despite the attempts at modernising the military during the Meiji period.  Meiji period Japanese military This was why the katana, a weapon obsolete for the mid-20th century, was still in use in the Japanese military during WW2.  Katana WW2 This also can be seen in the rather late adoption of the sub-machine gun in 1940, way behind many other militaries of Its time.  1940 Japanese submachine gun This can be explained by the fact that Japan\u2019s goal in the war was one of colonisation, using the war as an opportunity to capture South East Asia\u2019s resources.  South East Asia From these two examples, It's safe to say that national psychology can alter the development of weapons. That\u2019s all folks! ",
