            "answer_text": "Well, tanks count as weapons, right? So let\u2019s looks at those:  Germany Panzerkampfwagen VI Tiger Ac\u2019htung, Hanz, don\u2019t go full speed, you\u2019ll break the tracks From a viewpoint of an engineer, this thing is both a marvel and a disaster. The complexity used is impressive, and a lot over-engineered, but it\u2019s also its downfall, takes too much time to build, too much time to repair, use too much fuel, weight too much and is slow. But was it great for tank vs tank? Yes. The psychology of the german was we need the best, no matter the cost, only the strongest will survive and one unit is the only one needed.  USSR t-34 (all versions) Ivan, can you also feel that breeze? The t-34 is cheap. Really, really cheap. USSR made a lot of them, and it was a shady work: steel plates were cut to size grossly, welds were made rapidly, track links weren\u2019t bolted (t-34 had anvil pieces affixed to the hull to reput in place the linking pieces as the tank move, thus the \u201cclack-clack-clack\u201d sound)\u2026 So it was not rare for them to break down before seeing battle. But! IT WAS CHEAP! And what is cheap can be mass produced more! And mass produced it was, Hitler himself couldn\u2019t grasp how the russian army was able to spade as much tank as they did. USSR philosophy was that strength is equal to number, it didn\u2019t matter if that strength was of poor quality, just add more numbers.  USA M4 (all versions) American (late) entry into the war let them observe what the other fielded and took their time to conceive their medium tank. It\u2019s reliable (mostly), can fight (poorly against stronger armor but can) and can be easily upgraded (more or less). It perform quite well against infantry, bounce a stray cannon shot here and there, but don\u2019t expect it to be able to handle a 88m to the face. Albeit slower than t-34, it can still outpace easily the tiger. It greatest strength was ease of repair and like I said, upgrade-ability. USA philosophy was not to go with number (albeit it did) like URSS, nor with strength like germany, but to have versatility. I could for other nation, but I think I would lose the usual uninterested people, so I won\u2019t bother. ",
