            "answer_text": "Not especially. It tells us more about what resources they had available, what their priorities were, and how they intended to fight. For instance: the M4 Sherman, frequently derided, yet built in large numbers to a specification that dated from June 1940, when the best tanks in the world were thought to be the German PZKW IV. They were to be made using heavy truck drive components\u2014to avoid needing additional resources designing those components\u2014and to weigh no more than 40 tons\u2014because no winch could hoist a larger weight over the side of a ship and into a landing craft. The Army needed the vehicle fast to train the troops, develop doctrine, and build the units before the US was sucked into the war. They didn\u2019t care that it could barely defeat the PZKW IV because tank-on-tank warfare was not in US doctrine. Yeah, that\u2019s what they were thinking in June of \u201840. And there were thousands of such decisions made about nearly everything. ",
